            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Harpreet Singh\u2019s story is one of flavor, resilience, and the sweet taste of a dream redefined. Born not in San Francisco, but in the fertile fields of Yuba City, he was the son of Punjabi Sikh immigrants who came to California to work the land. His childhood was steeped in the aroma of his mother\u2019s kitchen\u2014cumin, coriander, and turmeric\u2014and the weight of his parents' expectations. They envisioned a stable future for him, one far from the toil of the fields, which led him to San Francisco State University to earn a practical Bachelor's degree in Business Administration.\n\nHe followed their path for a decade, working a respectable but soul-crushing logistics job downtown. The dot-com bust of the early 2000s, which saw him laid off, became an unexpected liberation. With a small severance and a burning passion, Harpreet traded his keyboard for a knife set. He started at the bottom, washing dishes in a SoMa restaurant and absorbing every technique he could. His business degree, once a symbol of conformity, became his secret weapon. He understood supply chains, profit margins, and marketing in a way other aspiring chefs didn't.\n\nAfter years of relentless work and saving, he opened \"Tandoori & Tide\" in the Inner Richmond. The restaurant is his heart manifest: a modern, Cal-Indian eatery that fuses the Punjabi flavors of his youth with fresh, local Bay Area ingredients. It\u2019s a neighborhood gem, not a tourist trap.\n\nHis daily routine is a ritual. He wakes before dawn to visit wholesale markets, then takes the 38-Geary Muni bus\u2014his 2.5-mile commute a time for quiet reflection. He and his wife, Jasleen, a high school teacher, live in a modest apartment above a bakery. Their daughter, Priya, now studies environmental science at UC Davis, forging her own path. Harpreet knows his regulars by name and considers his staff family. His hope is no longer for wealth, but for legacy. He dreams of mentoring a young chef to one day take over Tandoori & Tide, ensuring the warm, fragrant heart of his community continues to beat long after he hangs up his apron."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  \nHe remembers being seven, standing on a stool in his mother\u2019s Yuba City kitchen. She was making daal for the farmhands, the air thick with the smell of sizzling mustard seeds. His small hands struggled to shape roti, but she just smiled, her bangles chiming as she corrected his form. He felt the warmth not just from the stove, but from the act of feeding people who worked the earth. It was a feeling of profound belonging that planted a seed in him, one that would take decades to fully sprout.\n\n2.  \nThe box felt impossibly light in his hands as he walked out of the downtown high-rise for the last time. Ten years in logistics, gone in a sterile, ten-minute meeting. The initial sting of failure quickly gave way to a dizzying, terrifying freedom on the crowded sidewalk. He looked at his reflection in a window and didn\u2019t recognize the man in the suit. For the first time, the future was not a straight line laid out by his parents, but a blank page. The fear tasted surprisingly like hope.\n\n3.  \nIt was the first packed Saturday night at Tandoori & Tide. The tiny dining room buzzed with life, a symphony of chatter and clinking glasses. Leaning against the kitchen doorframe, sweat stinging his eyes, he saw Jasleen at a small table, her expression radiant. He caught the scent of his Dungeness crab curry mingling with cardamom from the chai. This wasn't just a restaurant; it was his parents' resilience and his own quiet rebellion, served on a plate. The gratitude he felt almost buckled his knees.\n\n4.  \nPriya was sixteen, spreading textbooks across their small living room floor. She spoke passionately about watershed restoration, her hands tracing invisible rivers in the air. He saw his own fire in her\u2014not for food, but for the very land his own parents had toiled. In that moment, he understood. His difficult choice to leave a \"stable\" career had given his daughter freedom to define her own. His legacy wasn't just the restaurant; it was her courage to choose the earth over an office, a choice he never had.\n\n5.  \nHe watched the familiar storefronts of the Richmond slide by from his seat on the 38-Geary. It was 6 a.m., the bus rumbling steadily westward. In his bag were fresh petrale sole, and in his mind, turmeric leaf and fennel were already coming together. An elderly woman he knew from the restaurant boarded, and they exchanged a warm, silent nod. This commute, once a path to a life he didn't want, was now his daily pilgrimage. He wasn\u2019t building an empire; he was tending his small, fragrant corner of the world."
